Why Use TypeScript with React?

TypeScript helps catch bugs earlier by enforcing types during development. In React, it improves component reliability, reduces runtime errors, and makes your code easier to understand and maintain.

Setting Up React with TypeScript

npm create vite@latest my-app --template react-ts

We use Vite because it’s fast, modern, and supports TypeScript out of the box.

Typing Props in Functional Components

type ButtonProps = {
  label: string;
  disabled?: boolean;
};

export default function Button({ label, disabled = false }: ButtonProps) {
  return <button disabled={disabled}>{label}</button>;
}

Optional props are marked with a question mark (?). TypeScript enforces that components receive the correct prop types.

Typing useState and useRef

const [count, setCount] = useState<number>(0);
const inputRef = useRef<HTMLInputElement>(null);

Typing hooks ensures consistency and prevents passing invalid data into your state or refs.

Typing API Data

interface Post {
  id: number;
  title: string;
  body: string;
}

axios.get<Post[]>("/api/posts").then(response => {
  console.log(response.data);
});

Typing your data responses avoids undefined errors and improves code readability.

Concept | Example | Benefit

Props typing | type Props {} | Prevents wrong props

State typing | useState<number> | Ensures valid state

API typing | axios.get<Post[]> | Safe API responses

Mini Project Step

Convert your existing React Todo component to TypeScript by typing props, state, and functions. Add an interface for todo items and enforce stricter code quality.

